  EN-TRANSLATIONS (für Fedor zur Tonprüfung — alle Headings + Body + Hint):
    S1 H: "In April 2024 cannabis was partly legalised in Germany."
    S1 B: "With the Konsumcannabisgesetz, decades of prohibition culture ended. Suddenly
          questions are surfacing publicly that rarely came up before: is cannabis
          addictive? Does it damage the brain? Is it medicine — or a gateway drug? The
          Hamburg Institute for Interdisciplinary Addiction and Drug Research (ISD)
          wanted to know what the population actually believes — and how much of it is
          correct."
    S2 H: "Everyone in Germany has an opinion about cannabis."
    S2 B: "Online, at the kitchen table, in the waiting room. Statements like 'Cannabis
          makes you unmotivated', 'Cannabis relieves pain', 'It's a gateway drug' or
          'It's harmless' pepper everyday life. The ISD collected them systematically:
          from an online survey of 1.041 people, from interviews with 60 prevention
          professionals, and from a media analysis."
    S2 hint: "Hover over the speech bubbles to read statements."
    S3 H: "From thousands of statements, 42 testable theses remained."
    S3 B: "The collected views were bundled, abstracted, and grouped by topic:
          substance-related (3), overarching (4), physical (10), psychological (11),
          combined physical-psychological (4), social (5), and legal (2). 42 theses
          that circulate as myths — some true, some not."
    S4 H: "Each thesis was tested against the research literature."
    S4 B: "In a systematic literature review, each of the 42 theses was evaluated against
          current scientific evidence — on a four-level scale: true, rather true, rather
          false, false. 16 are correct. 6 are mostly correct. 11 are mostly false. 7 are
          false. For 2 theses the current research does not allow a clear verdict."
    S4 hint: "Tap a card to read it."
    S5 H: "Then we asked 2.795 people what they hold to be true."
    S5 B: "A population survey in Germany with 2.097 adults (18–70), 555 minors (16–17),
          and 143 members of cannabis cultivation associations. For each of the 42
          theses, five indicators were measured — across five target groups: adults,
          minors, current consumers, young adults, and parents of minors."
    S6 H: "Three questions. Three findings."
    S6 B: "Who knows what? Best known: 'Cannabis relieves pain' — 77% of consumers.
          Least known: 'Cannabis is a panacea' — only 12% of adults know this statement
          at all. Who judges correctly? On road safety, adults score 92 of 100 — near
          perfect agreement with science. On 'general motivation loss' only 25 of 100 —
          most are wrong. Which myths need education? Prevention significance combines
          personal importance and knowledge gap. Three topics stand out: 'Cannabis
          relieves pain' (34 pts), 'Cannabis is a gateway drug' (28 pts) — and for
          minors especially: 'The law will increase consumption' (23 pts)."
    S6 hint: "Scroll on — the heatmap loads three indicators in sequence."
    S7 H: "We trust the right people — but we don't ask them."
    S7 B: "Doctor's offices and pharmacies enjoy the highest credibility as a
          health-information source — across all target groups, with 92 trust points.
          But: only 37% of minors actually look for information there. Among adults
          it's 60%. Minors ask relatives instead (53%) — who are similarly trusted but
          often poorly informed themselves. Influencers receive only 49 of 100 trust
          points — but 17% of minors name them as a source of health information."
    S8 H: "What we built from this."
    S8 B: "This site turns the CaRM findings into formats for different needs: 42
          factsheets with the scientific classification, sources and explanations per
          myth. A self-test that compares your own knowledge with the survey results.
          Four data dashboards for the general audience, parents, prevention
          professionals, and researchers. FAQ sorted by topic and target group."
    S9 H: "Who's behind the study."
    S9 B: "The CaRM study was conducted by the Hamburg Institute for Interdisciplinary
          Addiction and Drug Research (ISD) — with Christian Schütze, Dr. Bernd
          Schulte, Dr. Sven Buth, Dr. Peter Degkwitz, Moritz Rosenkranz and Harald
          Lahusen. The project was funded by the Federal Institute for Public Health
          (BIÖG). Methodological consultation was provided by an expert panel from
          cannabis prevention, addiction research, and public health."

